This article is a letter from President Barack Obama to the Speaker of the House and the President Pro Tempore of the Senate. In the letter, Obama provides a report on the ongoing global deployments of U.S. Armed Forces equipped for combat. He mentions that since 2001, the United States has conducted combat operations in Afghanistan against al-Qa'ida and the Taliban, and has deployed forces to various locations in support of overseas operations. He states that additional measures will be taken, as necessary, to protect U.S. citizens and interests. The letter also discusses the success of U.S. operations in degrading al-Qa'ida's capabilities and eliminating the Taliban's leadership in Afghanistan. It mentions the number of U.S. forces in Afghanistan and the authorization of the International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) by the UN Security Council. The letter states that the United States continues to detain al-Qa'ida and Taliban fighters at Guantanamo Bay and supports Iraq in maintaining security and stability. It also mentions U.S. efforts in enhancing counterterrorism capabilities globally, including the deployment of combat-equipped forces in the Horn of Africa region and conducting maritime interception operations. The letter further discusses U.S. contributions to peacekeeping efforts in Kosovo through the NATO-led Kosovo Force (KFOR) and the establishment of the Kosovo Security Force (KSF). President Obama concludes the letter by stating that he has directed the participation of U.S. Armed Forces in these operations based on his constitutional authority as Commander in Chief and Chief Executive.